[{"page_rating_contents": 0, "page_rating": 0, "tags": [], "age": null, "date_published": "2024-01-29T22:44:04+00:00", "album": "", "thumbnail": null, "title": "TikTok goes full YouTube", "dead": false, "vote": 0, "description": "<figure>\n      <img alt=\"TikTok logo\" src=\"https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/9RVIENaufXwxmOysObAsNw_FMYE=/0x0:2040x1360/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73095331/acastro_200713_1777_tikTok_0002.0.0.jpg\" />\n        <figcaption>Illustration: Alex Castro / The Verge</figcaption>\n    </figure>\n\n  <p id=\"g73e5z\">Vertical video platform TikTok wants users to turn their phones around and start shooting horizontal videos \u2014 long ones, too.</p>\n<p id=\"RPInLo\">TikTok appears to be <a href=\"https://www.threads.net/@mattnavarra/post/C2sY3E4IvpV/?igshid=MzRlODBiNWFlZA%3D%3D\">incentivizing creators</a> to start posting horizontal videos that are more than a minute long, according to a prompt seen by creators <a href=\"https://www.tiktok.com/t/ZT8nhhmRN/\">@candicedchap</a> and <a href=\"https://www.tiktok.com/@kenlyealtumbiz/video/7328197656138976558\">@kenlyealtumbiz</a>. The platform says it will \u201cboost\u201d these videos within 72 hours of posting. Creators who\u2019ve been on TikTok ", "bookmarked": false, "page_rating_visits": 0, "source": "https://www.theverge.com/rss/index.xml", "user": null, "comments": [], "language": "en", "source_obj__id": 61, "link": "https://www.theverge.com/2024/1/29/24054906/tiktok-youtube-horizontal-videos-creators", "permanent": false, "page_rating_votes": 0, "artist": null}, {"page_rating_contents": 0, "page_rating": 0, "tags": [], "age": null, "date_published": "2024-01-29T22:34:02+00:00", "album": "", "thumbnail": null, "title": "Microsoft says Apple\u2019s new App Store rules are \u2018a step in the wrong direction\u2019", "dead": false, "vote": 0, "description": "<figure>\n      <img alt=\"Apple Apps Photo Illustrations\" src=\"https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/H-gwsO_cnhD2m4C6sChmsMy5VEs=/0x0:3281x2187/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73095297/1246654654.0.jpg\" />\n        <figcaption>Photo by Jakub Porzycki/NurPhoto via Getty Images</figcaption>\n    </figure>\n\n  <p id=\"2LJPzs\">Apple\u2019s <a href=\"https://www.theverge.com/2024/1/26/24051823/apple-third-party-app-stores-50-cent-fee\">new plan</a> to comply with the European Union\u2019s tech regulations has already drawn criticism from Epic Games CEO <a href=\"https://www.theverge.com/2024/1/25/24050696/epic-games-tim-sweeney-apple-app-store-response\">Tim Sweeney</a> and <a href=\"https://www.theverge.com/2024/1/26/24052162/spotify-apple-app-store-tax-eu-dma\">Spotify</a>. Now Microsoft is weighing in with its own concerns, calling the App Store changes in the EU \u201ca step in the wrong direction.\u201d</p>\n<p id=\"TCQAWw\">Apple has proposed a new <a href=\"https://www.theverge.com/2024/1/26/24", "bookmarked": false, "page_rating_visits": 0, "source": "https://www.theverge.com/rss/index.xml", "user": null, "comments": [], "language": "en", "source_obj__id": 61, "link": "https://www.theverge.com/2024/1/29/24054943/microsoft-apple-app-store-dma-rule-change-response", "permanent": false, "page_rating_votes": 0, "artist": null}, {"page_rating_contents": 0, "page_rating": 0, "tags": [], "age": null, "date_published": "2024-01-29T19:56:35+00:00", "album": "", "thumbnail": null, "title": "Embracer lays off 97 Eidos employees and cancels new Deus Ex game", "dead": false, "vote": 0, "description": "<figure>\n      <img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/4WaxuVs_B5FY8Pn44cs5mub777k=/100x0:1180x720/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73094797/deus_ex.0.jpg\" />\n    </figure>\n\n  <p id=\"ZayjtM\">Embracer Group, the company attempting to forge <a href=\"https://www.theverge.com/2022/8/18/23311529/what-is-embracer-group-lord-of-the-rings-acquisition\">one video game publisher to rule them all</a>, has just presided over another round of layoffs. Eidos Montreal is letting go of 97 game developers and support staff, the company <a href=\"https://twitter.com/EidosMontreal/status/1752027685293801632/photo/1\">announced today on X</a>, shortly after <em>Bloomberg</em>\u2019s Jason Schreier scooped that the studio <a href=\"https://twitter.com/jasonschreier/status/1752015148213064092\">has canceled an unannounced <em>Deus Ex</em> video game</a>.</p>\n  <figure class=\"e-image\">\n        \n      <cite>Image: Eidos Montreal</cite>\n      <figcaption><em>\u201cThe global economic con", "bookmarked": false, "page_rating_visits": 0, "source": "https://www.theverge.com/rss/index.xml", "user": null, "comments": [], "language": "en", "source_obj__id": 61, "link": "https://www.theverge.com/2024/1/29/24054659/embracer-eidos-montreal-layoffs-deus-ex", "permanent": false, "page_rating_votes": 0, "artist": null}, {"page_rating_contents": 0, "page_rating": 0, "tags": [], "age": null, "date_published": "2024-01-29T19:50:56+00:00", "album": "", "thumbnail": null, "title": "The Kobo Elipsa 2E, our favorite ebook reader for taking notes, is $50 off", "dead": false, "vote": 0, "description": "<figure>\n      <img alt=\"The new Kobo Elipsa 2E on a desk surrounded by papers.\" src=\"https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/l-IkVS1hpPEEYw3ALrticNLEs_s=/0x1:1920x1281/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73094785/KoboElipsa2e.0.jpg\" />\n        <figcaption><em>There\u2019s a lot to like about the Kobo Elipsa 2 compared to something like the Kindle Scribe, especially with today\u2019s discount.</em> | Image: Kobo</figcaption>\n    </figure>\n\n  <p id=\"0KiVWe\">As much as I like physical books, I\u2019m planning a move and considering consolidating my collection to make that process more painless. You might be in the same boat, or perhaps you want a more convenient way to knock out your beefy reading list for the new year. If that sounds like you, you might want to consider the <strong>Kobo Elipsa 2E</strong>, which is currently <a href=\"https://go.redirectingat.com?id=66960X1514734&amp;xs=1&amp;url=https%3A%2F%2Fus.kobobooks.com%2Fproducts%2Fkobo-elipsa-2e&amp;referrer=theverge.com&amp;", "bookmarked": false, "page_rating_visits": 0, "source": "https://www.theverge.com/rss/index.xml", "user": null, "comments": [], "language": "en", "source_obj__id": 61, "link": "https://www.theverge.com/2024/1/29/24054234/kobo-elipsa-2-ebook-reader-zendure-supermini-usb-c-charger-eve-smart-plug-deal-sale", "permanent": false, "page_rating_votes": 0, "artist": null}, {"page_rating_contents": 0, "page_rating": 0, "tags": [], "age": null, "date_published": "2024-01-29T19:36:48+00:00", "album": "", "thumbnail": null, "title": "GM should just bring back the Chevy Volt", "dead": false, "vote": 0, "description": "<figure>\n      <img alt=\"2017 Chevy Volt\" src=\"https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/aFF8qQp28kiui49oXY6kIExwcpU=/0x0:1500x1000/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73094761/akrales_160629_1114_A_0269.0.jpg\" />\n        <figcaption>Amelia Krales</figcaption>\n    </figure>\n\n  <p id=\"tPF1AF\">General Motors\u2019 shift from an internal combustion engine-producing company to one that makes electric motors is sputtering. EV sales are up, but growing slower than expected. The company\u2019s next-generation Ultium platform, in particular, isn\u2019t meeting expectations. GM\u2019s new electric trucks and SUVs seem perennially delayed \u2014 or full of buggy software. </p>\n<p id=\"k7tbmY\">I think I have an easy solution to a lot of these problems: bring back the Chevy Volt. </p>\n<p id=\"jgvKJg\">Remember the Volt, GM\u2019s scrappy Toyota Prius fighter from the mid-2010s? The company was lauded when it first came out in 2010 as a prescient bet on vehicles with electric powertrains. And it was undeniably a ve", "bookmarked": false, "page_rating_visits": 0, "source": "https://www.theverge.com/rss/index.xml", "user": null, "comments": [], "language": "en", "source_obj__id": 61, "link": "https://www.theverge.com/2024/1/29/24054578/gm-chevy-bolt-hybrids-ev-sales-ultium", "permanent": false, "page_rating_votes": 0, "artist": null}, {"page_rating_contents": 0, "page_rating": 0, "tags": [], "age": null, "date_published": "2024-01-29T18:59:57+00:00", "album": "", "thumbnail": null, "title": "The $10 trillion benefits of overhauling our food system", "dead": false, "vote": 0, "description": "<figure>\n      <img alt=\"A hand holds one bundle of chard above a pile of more bundles.\" src=\"https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/-iPBjLy7TjE9inHawwqYH00ZK9A=/0x380:4065x3090/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73094607/1242156040.0.jpg\" />\n        <figcaption><em>Bundles freshly harvested chard.</em> | Photo by Waltraud Grubitzsch/picture alliance via Getty Images</figcaption>\n    </figure>\n\n  <p id=\"mMQzVI\">One of the most ambitious assessments yet of our global food system calculates the health, environmental, and economic losses of business as usual. It also outlines what governments can do to reap trillions of dollars\u2019 worth of benefits by producing food more sustainably. </p>\n<p id=\"JpHEuz\">All in all, the damages caused by the current system \u2014 how food is produced, marketed, and consumed \u2014 add up to $15 trillion in losses a year. That includes health costs associated with poor nutrition, biodiversity loss, climate change, and other environmental harms. \u201cIn ", "bookmarked": false, "page_rating_visits": 0, "source": "https://www.theverge.com/rss/index.xml", "user": null, "comments": [], "language": "en", "source_obj__id": 61, "link": "https://www.theverge.com/2024/1/29/24054325/food-sustainable-agriculture-diet-benefits-report", "permanent": false, "page_rating_votes": 0, "artist": null}, {"page_rating_contents": 0, "page_rating": 0, "tags": [], "age": null, "date_published": "2024-01-29T18:46:49+00:00", "album": "", "thumbnail": null, "title": "The MSI Claw will not have a VRR screen after all", "dead": false, "vote": 0, "description": "<figure>\n      <img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/18SUKmovcUknrCBG0jTGH-tHXvU=/0x0:1995x1330/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73094538/msi_claw_3_2.0.jpg\" />\n        <figcaption><em>The MSI Claw gaming handheld.</em> | Image: MSI</figcaption>\n    </figure>\n\n  <p id=\"7vyy82\">The <a href=\"https://www.theverge.com/24030779/msi-claw-portable-gaming-pc-hands-on\">MSI Claw</a> will be one of the first handheld gaming PCs with an Intel Core Ultra processor inside \u2014 but despite what the company told us at CES 2024, it won\u2019t have a variable refresh rate (VRR) screen. To my knowledge, the Asus ROG Ally is the only handheld with that dynamic gameplay smoothing display feature, and it\u2019s <a href=\"https://www.theverge.com/23719210/asus-rog-ally-review#:~:text=I%20wish%20it%20had%20the%20Ally%E2%80%99s%20variable%20refresh%20rate%20screen%20to%20make%20my%20games%20as%20smooth.%C2%A0\">one of its biggest advantages</a>. I\u2019m disappointed the MSI Claw won\u2019t have", "bookmarked": false, "page_rating_visits": 0, "source": "https://www.theverge.com/rss/index.xml", "user": null, "comments": [], "language": "en", "source_obj__id": 61, "link": "https://www.theverge.com/2024/1/29/24054478/msi-claw-no-vrr-screen", "permanent": false, "page_rating_votes": 0, "artist": null}, {"page_rating_contents": 0, "page_rating": 0, "tags": [], "age": null, "date_published": "2024-01-29T18:10:23+00:00", "album": "", "thumbnail": null, "title": "Anker\u2019s MagSafe-friendly 622 Magnetic Battery is half off right now", "dead": false, "vote": 0, "description": "<figure>\n      <img alt=\"Anker\u2019s 621 Magnetic Battery (MagGo) holding up an iPhone with its kickstand on a desk.\" src=\"https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/XE-jIho5xpllVpOSFhmebJskPPc=/0x0:2040x1360/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73094401/226451_MagSafe_Buying_Guide_ADiBenedetto_0015.0.jpg\" />\n        <figcaption><em>You can buy the portable power bank on sale at Amazon in a variety of colors.</em> | Photo by Antonio G. Di Benedetto / The Verge</figcaption>\n    </figure>\n\n  <p id=\"wreJWy\">Anker\u2019s <a href=\"https://www.theverge.com/24027019/anker-qi2-hands-on-magsafe-speed\">new Qi2-compatible chargers</a> may be capturing all the attention, but that doesn\u2019t mean older devices like the <strong>Anker 622 Magnetic Battery (MagGo)</strong> aren\u2019t worth a look. The portable, 5,000mAh<em> </em>charger may not be as fast as Anker\u2019s new <a href=\"https://howl.me/clwyfYlcOju\">Qi2 MagGo Power Bank</a>, but it\u2019s still<strong> </strong><a href=\"https://www.theverge.com/23505", "bookmarked": false, "page_rating_visits": 0, "source": "https://www.theverge.com/rss/index.xml", "user": null, "comments": [], "language": "en", "source_obj__id": 61, "link": "https://www.theverge.com/2024/1/29/24054421/anker-622-magnetic-battery-maggo-magnetic-qi-charger-deal-sale", "permanent": false, "page_rating_votes": 0, "artist": null}, {"page_rating_contents": 0, "page_rating": 0, "tags": [], "age": null, "date_published": "2024-01-29T18:01:36+00:00", "album": "", "thumbnail": null, "title": "Microsoft stole my Chrome tabs, and it wants yours, too", "dead": false, "vote": 0, "description": "<figure>\n      <img alt=\"The Microsoft Edge web browser logo against a swirling blue background.\" src=\"https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/nvrvcV4_bsTCA6pjm0g9FIz7g7Q=/0x0:2040x1360/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73094363/STK148_Microsoft_Edge_1.0.jpg\" />\n        <figcaption>Image: The Verge</figcaption>\n    </figure>\n\n  <p id=\"0nE7TG\">Last week, I turned on my PC, installed a Windows update, and rebooted to find Microsoft Edge automatically open with the Chrome tabs I was working on before the update. I don\u2019t use Microsoft Edge regularly, and I have Google Chrome set as my default browser. Bleary-eyed at 9AM, it took me a moment to realize that Microsoft Edge had simply taken over where I\u2019d left off in Chrome. I couldn\u2019t believe my eyes.</p>\n<p id=\"DptQyh\">I never imported my data into Microsoft Edge, nor did I confirm whether I wanted to import my tabs. But here was Edge automatically opening after a Windows update with all the Chrome tabs I\u2019d been working ", "bookmarked": false, "page_rating_visits": 0, "source": "https://www.theverge.com/rss/index.xml", "user": null, "comments": [], "language": "en", "source_obj__id": 61, "link": "https://www.theverge.com/24054329/microsoft-edge-automatic-chrome-import-data-feature", "permanent": false, "page_rating_votes": 0, "artist": null}, {"page_rating_contents": 0, "page_rating": 0, "tags": [], "age": null, "date_published": "2024-01-29T17:30:00+00:00", "album": "", "thumbnail": null, "title": "A scene-y newsletter launches a scene-y social network", "dead": false, "vote": 0, "description": "<figure>\n      <img alt=\"Perfectly Imperfect founder Tyler Bainbridge\" src=\"https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/WgodkeEMYhjuKzEnlTLRY1UocSM=/0x0:2400x1600/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73094259/self_portrait.0.jpg\" />\n        <figcaption>Perfectly Imperfect founder Tyler Bainbridge</figcaption>\n    </figure>\n\n\n  \t\t <p>The dream of the early internet is alive in PI.FYI, a new app spun out from <em>Perfectly Imperfect</em>.</p>\n  <p>\n    <a href=\"https://www.theverge.com/creators/24054294/perfectly-imperfect-pi-fyi-app-tyler-bainbridge\">Continue reading&hellip;</a>\n  </p>", "bookmarked": false, "page_rating_visits": 0, "source": "https://www.theverge.com/rss/index.xml", "user": null, "comments": [], "language": "en", "source_obj__id": 61, "link": "https://www.theverge.com/creators/24054294/perfectly-imperfect-pi-fyi-app-tyler-bainbridge", "permanent": false, "page_rating_votes": 0, "artist": null}, {"page_rating_contents": 0, "page_rating": 0, "tags": [], "age": null, "date_published": "2024-01-29T17:10:55+00:00", "album": "", "thumbnail": null, "title": "Sony\u2019s next PlayStation State of Play streams this week", "dead": false, "vote": 0, "description": "<figure>\n      <img alt=\"A Sony DualSense Edge controller resting on a PlayStation 5 with an orange background.\" src=\"https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/ch9SiWKhyjU3AryIKshdKfPJ_0k=/0x0:2040x1360/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73094220/236487_Sony_DualSense_Edge_AKrales_0016.0.jpg\" />\n        <figcaption>Photo by Amelia Holowaty Krales / The Verge</figcaption>\n    </figure>\n\n  <p id=\"lBICQp\">Not long after <a href=\"https://www.theverge.com/24041665/xbox-developer-direct-2024-news-announcements-trailers\">Xbox kicked off the year with a showcase</a> featuring <a href=\"https://www.theverge.com/24040391/indiana-jones-and-the-great-circle-gameplay-trailer-xbox-bethesda\">the first look at<em> Indiana Jones and the Great Circle</em></a>, <a href=\"https://blog.playstation.com/2024/01/29/state-of-play-returns-this-wednesday-2/\">Sony has announced</a> that it\u2019s holding a State of Play livestream later this week. It\u2019ll be 40 minutes long and will take place on January ", "bookmarked": false, "page_rating_visits": 0, "source": "https://www.theverge.com/rss/index.xml", "user": null, "comments": [], "language": "en", "source_obj__id": 61, "link": "https://www.theverge.com/2024/1/29/24054261/playstation-state-of-play-february-2024-date-stream", "permanent": false, "page_rating_votes": 0, "artist": null}, {"page_rating_contents": 0, "page_rating": 0, "tags": [], "age": null, "date_published": "2024-01-29T15:36:20+00:00", "album": "", "thumbnail": null, "title": "Samsung Galaxy S24 Ultra review: all that and AI", "dead": false, "vote": 0, "description": "<p>The Galaxy S24 Ultra is packed with top-tier hardware, but its highly touted AI features are hit-or-miss \u2014 and the price is higher than ever.</p>\n  <p>\n    <a href=\"https://www.theverge.com/24053907/samsung-galaxy-s24-ultra-review-ai-screen-camera-battery\">Continue reading&hellip;</a>\n  </p>", "bookmarked": false, "page_rating_visits": 0, "source": "https://www.theverge.com/rss/index.xml", "user": null, "comments": [], "language": "en", "source_obj__id": 61, "link": "https://www.theverge.com/24053907/samsung-galaxy-s24-ultra-review-ai-screen-camera-battery", "permanent": false, "page_rating_votes": 0, "artist": null}, {"page_rating_contents": 0, "page_rating": 0, "tags": [], "age": null, "date_published": "2024-01-29T15:12:29+00:00", "album": "", "thumbnail": null, "title": "Zoom meetings are about to get weirder thanks to the Vision Pro", "dead": false, "vote": 0, "description": "<figure>\n      <img alt=\"An image showing someone using Zoom on the Apple Vision Pro\" src=\"https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/7FSoBeH_NViYAaiEBNsuwRdHD_k=/80x0:944x576/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73093885/zoom_apple_vision_pr.0.jpg\" />\n        <figcaption>Image: Zoom</figcaption>\n    </figure>\n\n  <p id=\"DTc00V\">Zoom\u2019s Vision Pro app will launch alongside Apple\u2019s new headset on February 2nd and let wearers use its \u201cpersona\u201d (a digital avatar based on their face scans) during video calls. Whoever they\u2019re calling will see their facial expressions and hand movements as if they\u2019re not wearing a headset, much like <a href=\"https://www.theverge.com/2023/6/5/23750096/apple-vision-pro-headset-persona-facetime\">Apple\u2019s FaceTime app for the Vision Pro</a>.</p>\n<p id=\"QxHyvN\">The <a href=\"https://news.zoom.us/zoom-launches-new-app-for-apple-vision-pro-to-make-hybrid-collaboration-more-immersive/\">upcoming Zoom app</a> will also take advantage of the Vision Pro\u2019s augm", "bookmarked": false, "page_rating_visits": 0, "source": "https://www.theverge.com/rss/index.xml", "user": null, "comments": [], "language": "en", "source_obj__id": 61, "link": "https://www.theverge.com/2024/1/29/24054262/zoom-apple-vision-pro-app-persona", "permanent": false, "page_rating_votes": 0, "artist": null}, {"page_rating_contents": 0, "page_rating": 0, "tags": [], "age": null, "date_published": "2024-01-29T13:43:28+00:00", "album": "", "thumbnail": null, "title": "Amazon abandons $1.4 billion deal to buy Roomba maker iRobot", "dead": false, "vote": 0, "description": "<figure>\n      <img alt=\"A robot vacuum with mopping arm deployed. The arm is a circular section of the top case of the Roomba with a mop pad on the underside. It presses against the floor when in use.\" src=\"https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/rnaN_fS3bZTZw21krdy6_Ouxh8k=/0x0:2040x1360/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73093589/226425_Roomba_Combo_Review_JTuohy_0014.0.jpg\" />\n        <figcaption><em>One of iRobot\u2019s Roombas in action.</em> | Photo by Jennifer Pattison Tuohy / The Verge</figcaption>\n    </figure>\n\n  <p id=\"p1Kbbj\">Amazon\u2019s deal to buy Roomba maker iRobot is off, the <a href=\"https://media.irobot.com/2024-01-29-Amazon-and-iRobot-agree-to-terminate-pending-acquisition\">companies announced today</a>, after iRobot said the deal has \u201cno path to regulatory approval in the European Union.\u201d iRobot is also announcing that it\u2019s laying off around 350 employees, or around 31 percent of its workforce as <a href=\"https://investor.irobot.com/news-releases/news-r", "bookmarked": false, "page_rating_visits": 0, "source": "https://www.theverge.com/rss/index.xml", "user": null, "comments": [], "language": "en", "source_obj__id": 61, "link": "https://www.theverge.com/2024/1/29/24034201/amazon-irobot-acquisition-over-antitrust-regulator-scrutiny", "permanent": false, "page_rating_votes": 0, "artist": null}, {"page_rating_contents": 0, "page_rating": 0, "tags": [], "age": null, "date_published": "2024-01-29T11:30:56+00:00", "album": "", "thumbnail": null, "title": "Japan\u2019s Moon probe regains power after landing upside-down nine days ago", "dead": false, "vote": 0, "description": "<figure>\n      <img alt=\"A photograph taken of the SLIM probe on the Moon\u2019s surface by the LEV-2 robot.\" src=\"https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/rfqSbpxWFKC34GSc38nWT1PZaCg=/0x27:640x454/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73093347/GEq8kYaaYAAioZA.0.jpeg\" />\n        <figcaption><em>SLIM landed close to its target, but engine troubles during the descent saw the lander flipped upside-down and unable to properly recharge its solar batteries.</em> | Image: Japan Aerospace Exploration Agency (JAXA)</figcaption>\n    </figure>\n\n  <p id=\"NlJQal\">Japan\u2019s Smart Lander for Investigating Moon (SLIM) has been resurrected, over a week after the probe ran out of electricity following its troubled lunar touchdown on January 20th, leaving it upside-down and its solar panels pointing in the wrong direction. On Monday, the Japan Aerospace Exploration Agency <a href=\"https://twitter.com/SLIM_JAXA/status/1751766255810556340\">(JAXA) announced</a> that communication with the SLIM space", "bookmarked": false, "page_rating_visits": 0, "source": "https://www.theverge.com/rss/index.xml", "user": null, "comments": [], "language": "en", "source_obj__id": 61, "link": "https://www.theverge.com/2024/1/29/24054163/japan-slim-moon-probe-regains-power-solar-panels-lunar-lander", "permanent": false, "page_rating_votes": 0, "artist": null}, {"page_rating_contents": 0, "page_rating": 0, "tags": [], "age": null, "date_published": "2024-01-29T09:40:55+00:00", "album": "", "thumbnail": null, "title": "Nomad\u2019s first Qi2 charger is shipping now for $10 less than its MagSafe model", "dead": false, "vote": 0, "description": "<figure>\n      <img alt=\"Nomad Stand with iPhone charging.\" src=\"https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/TMlUz-Ez3T8LV6tQdSMj0hJNxLE=/0x2:7305x4872/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73093261/SRC_20230324_2584_Edit_2.0.jpg\" />\n        <figcaption><em>The Nomad Stand offers 15W of wireless iPhone fast charging for $100.</em> | Image: Nomad</figcaption>\n    </figure>\n\n  <p id=\"l7hxAQ\">Nomad\u2019s Stand is the latest Qi2 charger to hit the market, offering up to 15W of wireless charging speed to Qi2-compatible phones like the iPhone 15. The accessory was announced <a href=\"https://www.theverge.com/2023/12/20/24009185/nomad-stand-qi2-wireless-charger-price-fast-magsafe\">in late December</a>, but it\u2019s now shipping in a choice of black or white for <a href=\"https://www.anrdoezrs.net/links/8532386/type/dlg/sid/verge/https://nomadgoods.com/products/stand-qi2-white\" rel=\"sponsored nofollow noopener\" target=\"_blank\">$100 from Nomad\u2019s website</a>.</p>\n<p id=\"0ELJuH\">It\u2019s $100 price", "bookmarked": false, "page_rating_visits": 0, "source": "https://www.theverge.com/rss/index.xml", "user": null, "comments": [], "language": "en", "source_obj__id": 61, "link": "https://www.theverge.com/2024/1/29/24054150/nomad-stand-qi2-price-release-date-specs-details-15w-fast-charging-magsafe-iphone-15", "permanent": false, "page_rating_votes": 0, "artist": null}, {"page_rating_contents": 0, "page_rating": 0, "tags": [], "age": null, "date_published": "2024-01-29T00:35:23+00:00", "album": "", "thumbnail": null, "title": "Arc Search combines browser, search engine, and AI into something new and different", "dead": false, "vote": 0, "description": "<figure>\n      <img alt=\"Three screenshots showing Arc Search on an iPhone.\" src=\"https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/jlWBXqrVa08ODchiavKBW3PanT0=/0x0:4500x3000/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73092751/Arc_Search.0.jpg\" />\n        <figcaption>Arc Search browses the web for you, and then builds you the webpage you wanted. That\u2019s the idea, anyway. | Image: The Browser Company / David Pierce</figcaption>\n    </figure>\n\n  <p id=\"s2KaAL\">A few minutes ago, I opened the new Arc Search app and typed, \u201cWhat happened in the Chiefs game.\u201d That game, the AFC Championship, had just wrapped up. Normally, I\u2019d Google it, click on a few links, and read about the game that way. But in Arc Search, I typed the query and tapped the \u201cBrowse for me\u201d button instead. </p>\n<p id=\"ConnEx\"><a href=\"https://apps.apple.com/us/app/arc-search/id6472513080\">Arc Search</a>, the new iOS app from The Browser Company, which has been working on <a href=\"https://www.theverge.com/23462235/arc-web-b", "bookmarked": false, "page_rating_visits": 0, "source": "https://www.theverge.com/rss/index.xml", "user": null, "comments": [], "language": "en", "source_obj__id": 61, "link": "https://www.theverge.com/2024/1/28/24053882/arc-search-browser-web-app-ios", "permanent": false, "page_rating_votes": 0, "artist": null}]